Time Series Analysis

Exploring a Time Series of Air Passengers

Klarisa Sula

11/03/2025

Section 1: Introduction

The purpose of this project is to explore a time series using Meta’s Prophet forecasting system. We will be looking at a dataset of air passengers and interpreting its results.

1.1 Objectives:

  1. Analyse air passenger data over time
  2. Identify trends and seasonality
  3. Use the prophet model to predict future trends
  4. Interpret and summarise key findings

1.2 What does the air passenger data show us?

The dataset shows us the total number of passengers flying on aeroplanes each month from 1949 to 1960.

1.3 Why are we using Prophet?

  • It is easier to use than some other models
  • It detects seasonal patterns and trends
  • It predicts future trends in time series data

Section 2: Loading and Exploring the Data

2.1 Libraries we need

  • library(readr)
  • library(ggplot2)
  • library(prophet)
  • library(zoo)

2.2 Load the Dataset

# This will read and load our dataset into R Studio
air_passengers.df <- read_csv("~/Downloads/Air_Passengers_Time_Series.csv")
# Here we are turning our ds column to a year-month format
air_passengers.df <- data.frame(
  ds = zoo::as.yearmon(air_passengers.df$ds),
  y = air_passengers.df$y
)

# This will show us the first few rows of our dataset so we can see the layout  
head(air_passengers.df)
##         ds   y
## 1 Jan 1949 112
## 2 Feb 1949 118
## 3 Mar 1949 132
## 4 Apr 1949 129
## 5 May 1949 121
## 6 Jun 1949 135

Section 2.3 Plot the Data

# Plot the time series and label both axes
ggplot(air_passengers.df, aes(x = ds, y = y)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Number of Air Passengers per Month", x = "Year", y = "Number of Passengers")

Results:

  • The graph shows an upward trend for the number of passengers over time.
  • From this graph we can see that there are regular peaks and dips each year, which are called seasonal fluctuations. The peaks show that more people travel in the summer and the dips show that less people travel in the winter.

Section 3: Linear Regression Analysis

3.1 Linear Regression Model

We will now use a linear regression model to estimate how much the number of air passengers increases each year on average.

# Fit linear regression model
linear_regression_model <- lm(y ~ ds, data = air_passengers.df)
summary(linear_regression_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ ds, data = air_passengers.df)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -93.858 -30.727  -5.757  24.489 164.999 
## 
## Coefficients:

## ds              31.886      1.108   28.78   <2e-16 ***

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 46.06 on 142 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8536, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8526 
## F-statistic: 828.2 on 1 and 142 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
# Plot the linear regression model
plot(air_passengers.df$ds, air_passengers.df$y, type="p", xlab="Year", ylab="Number of Air Passengers")
lines(air_passengers.df$ds, fitted(linear_regression_model), col="red")

Results:

  • This linear regression model shows an increase in the number of passengers over the years.
  • The regression line shows an upward trend, which is what we expect.
  • The plots are slowly moving further away from the line. This might show that the data has some seasonal fluctuations which are increasing more and more each year.

Section 4: Decomposing the time series

4.1 Decomposition plot

We will now plot the decomposition of multiplicative time series to understand the patterns in the data.

air_passengers_time_series <- ts(air_passengers.df$y, start = c(1949, 1), frequency = 12)

# We will be generating a multiplicative decomposition
decomposed <- decompose(air_passengers_time_series, type = "multiplicative")

# Here we plot the decomposition of the time series
plot(decomposed)

Results:

  • The observed data shows an upward trend and regular peaks. This is a similar pattern to our first plot.
  • The trend data has removed the fluctuations, and it shows a smooth increase in the number of air passengers over time.
  • The seasonal data shows the regular peaks. The seasonality doesn’t change over the years, the peaks and dips stay the same.
  • The random noise data shows no pattern, so this means that the model did a good job of showing the trend.

Section 5: Applying Meta’s Prophet for Forecasting

5.1 Prophet Model

Here we will plot a graph that represents a time series forecast using Meta’s Prophet model.

m = prophet::prophet(air_passengers.df)

# This creates the future data frame for 8 months ahead
f = prophet::make_future_dataframe(m, periods=12, freq="month")

# This will generate the predictions
p = predict(m, f)
# This will plot the forecast
plot(m, p)

Results:

  • The plots show an increasing trend. The line which represents the forecast trend also shows an increase in passengers over time.
  • There is a shaded area around the line which represents the uncertainty interval. The uncertainty grows throughout the years.
  • The prediction that the forecast has given us is very accurate when we compare it to the observed data. It shows a similar peak and an increase in passengers.

5.2 Trend and Seasonality

# This will break down the forecast into trend and yearly seasonality
prophet_plot_components(m, p)

Results:

  • The number of passengers in the trend plot shows an upward trend.

  • The number of passengers in the yearly seasonality plot fluctuates. It peaks in the summer months and dips in the winter months.

Section 6: Conclusion

Our analysis shows that air travel has grown over the years, with clear seasonal patterns. We would expect the number of passengers to keep increasing after 1960, as the forecast prediction has shown us.
